When the activists of Momentum in my party voted for me to be reprimanded, I was not surprised.
After all, I am a member of a group of Labour Members who have recently been told that they are not welcome, all because of their own opinions.
My parliamentary colleague, Joan Ryan, was treated similarly because she opposed anti-Semitism.
In my case, the reprimand was due to a difference of opinion between me and Jeremy Corbyn.
The differences concerned the importance of responsible economic policy, national security and Europe. Ironically, Jeremy Corbyn opposed the position of previous leaders on these issues.
In the announcement on Friday of the Labour Party’s meeting in Nottingham East County, it was read: “We want the meetings to be open and productive.”
During my eight years as a member of the Labour Party, most of the Friday afternoon meetings of the General Committee looked like this.
Unfortunately, many meetings are going differently now, and the promise of a "more cordial and gentler" policy has long been forgotten, as far as it has ever been remembered.
It is becoming increasingly clear that the Labour Party does not tolerate different views. Each opinion is assessed in terms of compliance with the party leadership.
It all started shortly after Jeremy Corbyn took office as EU President, and my colleagues, who seemed to me to have similar views, began to expect me to change my direction and to take positions that I would not have agreed with before.
After every public speech – regardless of the content – I meet on social media with attacks calling for the withdrawal of nominations, the condemnation of centrism or the departure of the Labour Party.
It's not just my experience.
I am more fortunate than some of my colleagues, because the comments addressed to me are rather political in nature.
I admire the professionalism and determination of colleagues who experience daily treatment in a sexist or racist way, but do not avoid further action.
One of the most disappointing aspects of the current policy is the transition to the agenda with insults to others.
Last week, Jeremy Corbyn said the Labour Party should support a culture of tolerance.
In fact, we are no longer a group of people with different views. With every request for a “vote of distrust” and every change in the rules of choice, the party’s worldview is narrowed down.
Over the past two years, I have been repeatedly advised not to lean over and keep silent on certain issues. Then everything “would be okay”.
That’s not why I was involved in politics.
Since joining the Labour Party 32 years ago as a student as a result of the negligence of the Margaret Thatcher government that led to the disintegration of my school class, I have been trying to provide better public services for those in need – both as a local councillor and a minister.
I never hid my beliefs, even during the last election campaign.
Everyone in Nottingham East knew my position and they knew about differences of opinion with the party authorities.
To those who supported Friday’s proposal, I would like to say that I cannot understand the willingness to waste time and energy on the issue of my loyalty to the Labour leader in the face of an impending Brexit that will harm households, businesses and public services.
However, the most important message I am sending is not to Nottingham Momentum, but to my constituents (both Labour Party members and others): I am proud to be able to serve you. I promise that no threat of revocation of the nomination or the most opportune political goals of overcoming your best interests will discourage me from doing anything.
