“The sea belongs to us”: Bolivia’s sea-deprived hope that the court will reopen its way to the Pacific
Marines patrol the vicinity of a naval base in La Paz.
There are blue flags flying from public buildings.
In the ports of the Navy from Lake Titicaca to the Amazon, the motto appears: “The sea is ours by law.
It is our duty to recover him.”
In Bolivia’s inaccessible sea, the memory of the coastline lost to Chile in the bloody resource conflict of the 19th century is still alive. It’s like dreaming of sailing again in the Pacific Ocean.
Bolivia is awaiting the verdict of the International Court of Justice, which is due to be issued on October 1 after a five-year trial.
“Bolivia’s actions are gaining momentum. Residents are unanimous, optimistic and counting on a favorable verdict,” said Bolivian diplomat Roberto Calzadilla.
Many Bolivians across the country will watch the meeting of the International Court of Justice together. They hope that the organization based in The Hague will recognize Bolivia’s claim and, after decades of fruitless talks, Chile will have to enter independently into negotiations on granting the state.
Evo Morales, the charismatic Bolivian president who will face a controversial re-election battle next year, also hopes for a verdict on Monday.
“We are very close to returning to the Pacific,” he swore at the end of August.
However, some analysts argue that the chances of a favorable verdict for Bolivia are small and that even a favorable decision would not change much.
The United Nations body based in The Hague has no authority to grant Bolivia the territory of Chile. It also has reservations that it will not affect the settlement of any talks.
According to Paz Zárate, a Chilean specialist in international law, the decision of the International Court of Justice will be issued six months after the submission of the final arguments. Such a short time shows that the case “was not complicated”.
Unfortunately, the past four years have allowed Bolivia to move away from its goal.
“The issue of access to the sea has been taken over by the current Bolivian administration,” said Paz Zárate.
Morales’ relentless rhetoric deprived Chileans of any remnants of goodwill, she suggested.
Bolivia and Chile will resume talks at some point, but this will be very difficult in the face of the situation.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, the former president and representative of Bolivia in The Hague, disagreed with the view that the court’s decision-making process was extremely rapid.
Monday will bring Bolivia “a unique opportunity to begin a new era in relations with Chile” and the possibility of “ending a 139-year period of mutually beneficial disputes,” he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales — still one of Latin America’s most popular presidents — was using the issue of access to the sea as an element of political play.
“Pallivia will never renounce the right of access to the Pacific Ocean,” he added.
“The verdict is a great opportunity to see that we have to deal with the past.”
