John Edward: Language Skills Necessary for the Citizens of the World
Independent schools in Scotland are continually rejoicing in their scientific achievements – in 2018 they were able to boast of further outstanding exam results, backed by individual and collective successes in sports, art, music and other social endeavors.
Represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), schools attended by more than 30,000 students across Scotland strive to provide the best level of services to students and parents.
Independent schools are designed to prepare students for further and higher education, their chosen career path, and to indicate their role as world citizens.
As an educational sector that has the opportunity to develop and implement a curriculum tailored to the needs of the school, we see that modern languages are still popular and desirable subjects to choose from in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you speak to another person in a language that he understands, it goes to his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, it goes to his heart.”
This is a clear reminder that we cannot rely only on English when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
The results of the last exam this year show that languages rank first in the league rankings, with the highest proficiency rates occurring for independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages received a higher A grade.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 percent of students received a higher A grade in Mandarin, and 72 percent of German learners, 69 percent of French learners and 63 percent of Spanish learners also received an A grade.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as essential skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Currently, learning languages as subjects of choice is conducted in the same scope as learning STEM subjects (Strict Sciences, Technology, Engineering and Mathematics) as part of curricula in independent schools and elsewhere.
A 2014 survey conducted by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills found that 17 percent of candidates’ lack of language proficiency was due to difficulties in obtaining vacancies from employers.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly becoming a necessity to prepare young people to start a career.
These skills are essential in a globalized world with a growing number of jobs requiring language proficiency.
A lifelong skill, like learning a second language, will provide a huge advantage in the future — regardless of the path of professional development.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically increases the chances of a multilingual person in relation to the competition.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of more than 4,000 British adults, 75% of them could not speak a foreign language well enough to conduct a conversation, and French was the only language with a two-digit, two-digit percentage.
That’s why investing in teaching foreign languages is so important for today’s children.
Knowledge of several languages, in particular the languages of developing economies, will give children a greater chance of finding suitable employment.
In Scotland, each school will be different in terms of the languages it teaches.
Many schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages considered to be the most important for the UK in the 2020 perspective, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of the child’s interests, independent schools will always have many languages to choose from, which will be taught by specialized teaching staff in this area.
Scottish independent schools are committed to creating a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills they need to succeed – no matter what the future holds for them.
Today, there is no denying that in the international business environment, languages are still crucial to the future of the country, so it must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should be regarded as "international communication skills" (international communication skills).
Independent schools will continue to offer Scottish youth a wide choice, diversity and level.
That's just the way it should be.
John Edward, Chairman of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
