North Korea says “decisive no” to unilateral disarmament without confidence.
North Korea's foreign minister said on Saturday in a speech at the U.N. that the failure to lift sanctions only deepens North Korea's lack of confidence in the United States and there is no way that the country would unilaterally give up nuclear weapons in such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly that North Korea took “significant measures of goodwill” last year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling a nuclear test site and committing to non-proliferation of weapons and nuclear technology.
“We do not see any concrete response from the United States,” he said.
"Without trust in the United States, there will be no guarantee of our national security and under such circumstances there is no unilateral disarmament of North Korea."
While Ri reiterated North Korea’s well-known complaints about Washington’s reluctance to adopt a “gradual” approach to denuclearization, in which North Korea would be rewarded for taking steps gradually, his statement appeared to be significant, as the denounced one thing.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first ever summit between the incumbent president of the United States and the leader of North Korea, which took place on June 12 in Singapore, when Kim Jong Un pledged to work for the “denuclearity of Korea”.
North Korea expected a formal end to the Korean War (1950–1953), but the U.S. delegation announced that Pyongyang must first give up nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls for the easing of harsh international sanctions against North Korea.
“The United States insists on ‘denuclearization first’ and increases pressure through sanctions to achieve its goal in a coercive manner, even opposing the signing of a ‘war ending declaration,’” Ri said.
“The testimony that sanctions can throw us to our knees is the dream of people who behave ignorantly towards us.
The problem, however, is that the lack of lifting sanctions deepens our mistrust.”
Ri did not mention plans for a second summit between Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump, which the U.S. leader spoke about earlier this week at the UN.
Instead, the minister drew attention to three meetings between Kim Jong-un and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, after which he added: “If the party on the issue of denuclearization were South Korea, not the United States, then there would be no such thing.”
Despite this, the tone of Ri's speech was completely different from last year when he said at the UN General Assembly that targeting North Korea's missiles in the United States is inevitable after the "Mr. Evil President" rocket hits Trump.
This year, at the UN forum, Trump, who last year threatened North Korea’s “complete destruction,” praised Kim Jong Un for his courage to take steps toward disarmament, but also said there was still a lot of work to be done, and he also said that until the North’s sanctions are lifted, it will not be backed.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had not set a timeline, saying, “Whether it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo said on Thursday at the UN Security Council that “enforcement of the Security Council sanctions must be continued and ongoing until we establish a complete, final and verified denuclearization.”
Since 2006, the Security Council has unanimously tightened sanctions against North Korea, trying to stifle funding for Pyongyang’s nuclear program and ballistic missiles.
Pompeo met with Ri outside the UN General Assembly and later said he would return to Pyongyang next month in preparation for the second summit.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but his last visit cannot be called a success.
He left Pyongyang in July, saying progress had been made, after which within hours North Korea condemned him for “making gangster demands.”
North Korea pledged this month at a meeting with Moon Jae-in that it would dismantle the missile test site and nuclear facility if the United States takes “appropriate measures.”
He said Kim Jong Un had told him that the "appropriate measures" he cares about were security guarantees, which Trump had pledged to ensure in Singapore, and steps to normalize relations with Washington.
Harvard students attend a course on adequately long rest periods
A new course at Harvard University, which took place this year, provided all students with more sleep, aimed at combating the growing macho culture of learning by “caffeine-driven full-time students.”
Academic students from the best university in the world often have no idea about the basics of caring for themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, has developed a course that he says is the first of its kind in the United States.
To create the course, he was inspired by a speech on the impact of sleep deprivation on science.
“After the speech, a girl came up to me and said, ‘Why are you telling me this only now that I’m in my final year of college?’
She stated that no one had ever told her about the meaning of sleep, which surprised me,” The Telegraph said.
The course, which took place for the first time this year, explains to students how good sleep habits help to achieve good results in learning and sports, as well as improve the overall well-being of students.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the University Health Service, said the course was decided to be introduced after it was found that students suffered from severe sleep deprivation within a week.
The hourly course includes a number of interactive tasks.
One section includes an image of a dormitory room where students click coffee cups, curtains, exercises, and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, and how sleep deficiency affects sports performance, as well as how important it is to maintain regular sleep.
In another section, participants learn how long-term lack of sleep can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A map of the campus with interactive icons encourages participants to reflect on their daily routine.
“We know that this will not cause an immediate change in the behavior of students.
But we believe they have the right to know — just as everyone has the right to know the health effects of smoking cigarettes,” added Professor Czeisler.
A culture of pride from “whole-night science” still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students means an increasing problem of sleep deprivation.
Providing enough sleep of good quality should be a “secret weapon” for students to fight stress, exhaustion and anxiety, and even avoid weight gain, because lack of sleep causes the brain to go into starvation mode, so the student is constantly hungry — said.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Ceisler develop the course after taking part in one of his classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to push for the introduction of a course for the entire campus.
The next step, according to him, is to ask all postgraduate students to complete a similar degree program before moving to a competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students set an alarm to remind them when to go to sleep and when to get up, and that they be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" emitted by the screens of electronic devices and LED lighting, which can disrupt the daily rhythm and lead to a problem.
