Almanac: the inventor of the Geiger counter
And now the page of our edition "Sunday Morning" Almanach: September 30, 1882 — 136 years ago... the day on which the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger was born in Germany.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity, which eventually led to the creation of a device known as the Geiger counter.
Since then, the Geiger counter has become an element of both science and pop culture, as in the 1950 film Bells of Coronado, in which these seemingly improbable cowboy scientists Roy Rogers and Dale Evans appeared:
Man: "What the hell is that?"
Rogers: “It’s a Geiger counter that’s used to locate radioactive minerals like uranium.
When you put on these headphones, you will hear the effects of atoms emitted by radioactive minerals.”
Evans: “Now you hear something!”
Hans Geiger died in 1945, a few days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that bears his name has survived to this day.
