China has announced a 14 percent increase in the number of people living with HIV and suffering from AIDS.
More than 820,000 people are affected by the problem, as reported by the country’s health services.
Around 40,000 new cases were reported in the second quarter of 2018 alone.
The vast majority of new cases were sexually transmitted, which means a change from the past.
Traditionally, HIV spreads rapidly in some parts of China as a result of an infected blood transfusion.
However, the number of people infected with HIV in this way has been almost completely reduced, according to Chinese health officials at a conference in Yunnan province.
However, year-on-year, the number of people living with HIV and suffering from AIDS in China increased by 100,000.
Sexually transmitted HIV is a serious problem in the Chinese LGBT community.
Homosexuality was decriminalized in China in 1997, but discrimination against LGBT people is widespread.
Given the country’s conservative values, the study estimates that 70-90% of men who have sex with men will eventually marry a woman.
Many cases of transmission of the disease are due to insufficient protection during sex in these relationships.
Since 2003, the Chinese government has provided universal access to HIV medicines as part of efforts to combat this problem.
