The creator of the World Wide Web plans to launch a new Internet to compete with Google and Facebook platforms.
Tim Berners-Lee, the creator of the World Wide Web, is launching a startup to compete with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest project of the technology legend, Inrupt, is a company based on an open source platform — Solid — owned by Berners-Lee.
Solid allows users to choose where their data is stored and which people have access to specific information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that the goal of creating Inrupt was “domination of the world.”
“We have to do it now,” he said, referring to the startup.
“It’s a historic moment.”
The application uses the technology of the Solid platform to allow people to create their own “personal data online store” or other POD.
It can include contact lists, lists of things to do, a calendar, a music library, and other personal and professional tools.
It’s like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify available in one browser and at the same time.
A unique feature of an online store with personal data is that it is entirely up to the user who has access to what information.
The company calls this “personal empowerment through data.”
According to the company’s CEO, John Bruce, the idea of Inrupt is to provide the resources, processes, and relevant skills to help make the Solid platform available to all people.
Currently, the company includes Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, several developers employed to work on the project, and a community of volunteer developers.
Starting this week, tech developers around the world were able to create their own decentralized apps using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said he and his team are not talking to “Facebook and Google about whether to make a complete change that will turn all of their business models upside down from day to day.
“Don’t ask for permission.”
Berners-Lee wrote in a post on Medium on Saturday that “Inrupt’s mission is to provide commercial energy and ecosystem to help protect the integrity and quality of the new network built on the Solid platform.”
In 1994, Berners-Lee changed the Internet when he founded the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has done a lot in the debate on net neutrality.
Berners-Lee will remain the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
“I’m extremely excited to think about the next era in the development of the network,” Berners-Lee added.
