The National Trust is listening to the secret life of bats
A new study on the estate in the Scottish Highlands aims to show how bats use the landscape while harvesting food.
The results of the study are expected to shed new light on the conservation of these exceptional flying mammals and help guide future actions to protect them.
Research conducted by researchers from the National Trust for Scotland will cover common and small dwarfs, as well as brown long-eared bats and bats from the family of red nuts at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special registrars will be deployed in key locations around the estate to monitor bat activity throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct field research using portable detectors.
The expert sound analysis of all recordings aims to determine the frequency of signals sent by bats and how each species behaves.
A habitat map and report will then be developed to create a detailed picture of their behavior on a landscape scale.
Rob Dewar, Nature Conservation Advisor at NTS, hopes the results will reveal which habitats are most important to bats and how they are used by each of the species.
This information will help to identify the benefits of habitat management work, such as meadow management, as well as the best ways to maintain forest areas for bats and other related species.
The populations of bats in Scotland and throughout the UK have declined significantly over the last century.
They are at risk of construction and development work, which affects the shrubs and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting installations can also pose a threat, as can fly glues and some chemicals used in building materials, and even domestic cats.
Butterflies are not really blind.
However, because of their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more helpful than their eyes in catching prey.
They use a complicated echolocation technique to find worms and obstacles in their path.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of over 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes bats very seriously.
