She added: "I was greatly helped by a woman who was a manager at a company. She said that she also cries when she's angry, but she invented a way that when she gets nervous and starts crying, she says to the person she's talking to 'You probably think I'm sad because she's sad.
I'm mad.
And he's still doing his thing.
I thought it was genius.”
Tears are acceptable as a way out of anger in part because they are basically misunderstood.
One of my clearest memories of one of the first jobs in a male-dominated office is how I once started to cry with an unspeakable rage. A certain elderly woman — a cool driver, who was always a bit scared of me — grabbed me.
“Never let them see you cry,” she said.
“They don’t know you’re angry.
They think you're sad, and they're glad they've baked you."
Patricia Schroeder of the Democratic Party, then a member of Congress from Colorado, worked with Gary Hart on his presidential campaign.
In 1987, when Hart was caught with a lover on a boat called Monkey Business and withdrew from the race, frustrated to the point that Patricia realized she could actually consider running for president on her own.
“It wasn’t a thoughtful decision,” she told me, laughing, 30 years later.
“There were seven other candidates before the election and the last thing they needed was another one.
Someone has called this situation ‘The Snow Queen and the Seven Dwarfs.’”
As the campaign had been going on for a long time, Schroeder lagged behind in raising funds and promised herself that she would not join the race unless she raised $2 million.
It was a battle doomed to lose.
She discovered that some of her supporters, who gave men $1,000, had only $250 for her.
“Do they think I have any discounts?” she wondered.
During her speech, in which she announced that she would not be conducting a formal campaign, she was so overwhelmed with emotions — gratitude to the people who supported her, frustration with the system that made it so difficult for her to raise money and turn to her voters for sex, not for delegates, and in public.
“You might think I’ve gone through a nervous breakdown,” she said.
“You might think I’m sponsored by Kleenex.
I remember wondering what they'd write on my grave.
'Crying?'"
What benefits can the economic war between the United States and China bring to Beijing
The sweepstakes starting the economic war between the US and China have been daunting and while the battle is still ongoing, in the long run, the conflict between these countries may be beneficial to Beijing, experts say.
The first warning was issued this year by U.S. President Donald Trump, imposing tariffs on key Chinese exports, including solar panels, steel and aluminum.
The most significant escalation occurred this week following the introduction of new tariffs on goods worth $200 billion (<0xC2><0xA3>150 billion), which resulted in taxation of half of all goods entering the US from China.
