I'm full of admiration for the opponents.
They played a lot better than us.”
Information on flowering — in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota plankton density decreases
A recent report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general decline in plankton density in some parts of the Gulf of Tampa.
According to the FWC, the presence of the streaked flower has been recorded in the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, suggesting that its density is decreasing.
It spans about 209 kilometres of coastline, from the north of Pinellas County to the south of Lee County.
The highlights can be found about 16 kilometers from the coast of Hillsborough County, but compared to the previous week in fewer places.
The inflorescence was also observed in Pasco County.
Last week, the average concentration of the County's low-plankton county near the coast and in the waters of Pinellas County was recorded, low to medium near the coast of Hillsborough County, natural to high in Manatee County, natural to high in coastal and in the waters of Sarasota County, natural to medium in the county of Charlotte County.
Airway irritation is still reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
Last week, however, there were no reports of them in northwest Florida.
